snippet: An investigation into Google’s Street View project was left unresolved because the engineer in charge declined to talk, according to an interim report.
abstract: Interim Federal Communications report says investigation into Google's Street View project is unresolved because the engineer in charge of the project cited his Fifth Amendment right and declined to talk; Google maintains the data gathering was unauthorized, but the engineer maintains other people at the company knew about it; Google and the FCC are wrangling over how much information can be revealed in the final report, which privacy advocates say is only a start.

byline.original: By DAVID STREITFELD and EDWARD WYATT
byline.contributor: Kevin J. O’Brien and Somini Sengupta contributed reporting.

lead_paragraph: An investigation into Google’s Street View project was left unresolved because the engineer in charge declined to talk, according to an interim report.
